    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.18-20_0001b" />

                <note type="curatorial">205 Neihardt Collection May 16, 1912</note>

                <note type="authorial">You will like to know that Lyman Bryson, who was in the hospital where you saw him, is to have a poem in the <title>"Forum"</title>.</note>
                
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>For a week I have been wanting to write you about my joy in that wonderful poem of yours which was printed in <title>Current Literature.</title>. If you keep on writing poems like that and I am so
                
                <fw type="curatorial">18</fw>
                        
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.18-20_0002"/>        
                                                                                                                                                    <fw type="curatorial">19</fw>
                
                blessed as to read them (as I certainly shall) I shall be able to hear overtures and all sorts of <unclear>platonic</unclear> melodies. That is an exquisite thing! I really <emph><hi rend="underline">have</hi></emph> no words to tell you how it makes me feel. I should have to write a poem to do it; a poem that could say far more than was in the words it was made of &#8212; and that is beyond my power.</p>
                    
                <p>But before this you have a paper which gives you a hint of how we are feeling. Keene wanted that poem to reach as many Nebraska readers as possible.</p>
                    
                <p>I am sending you and Mona and <emph><hi rend="underline">your mother</hi></emph>, my
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.18-20_0001a"/>                                                                                                                                   
                
                little girl. Compared with your little girl she isn't much, but she's all I have.</p>
                    
                <p>Give my most affectionate greeting to your mother and to your wife and to your daughter, and to the poet who gave us that poem.</p>
                <closer>
                                                                                            <salute>Always</salute>
                
                                                                                            <signed>Avery Abbott.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><del>Found in</del></note>
                
            </div1>
            
            
